Read more: https://github.com/shuding/react-wrap-balancer#browser-support-information"))};self.__wrap_n!=1&&self.__wrap_b(":R4tm:",1)Despite an economic downturn, fewer companies are applying for reconstruction - a form of bankruptcy protection. This is the lowest number in over ten years and might lead to more companies going bankrupt, warns Christer √ñstlund from Svensk N√§ringsliv. Many companies that could have been restructured are going bankrupt. This is unfortunate, says √ñstlund, because bankruptcy often results in significant capital destruction and can lead to job losses. Suppliers to the bankrupt companies lose more money, and they are likely to lose large parts of their claims in the bankruptcy. This creates a domino effect that spreads among many companies.In the first nine months of the year, 120 applications were submitted to courts around the country, a decrease of 40% compared to the same period last year. One reason may be that the rules for reconstructions were changed last year, according to √ñstlund. The new rules are not as well adapted for smaller companies as one would wish. It is now more expensive to go through a reconstruction compared to the previous legislation. This means that smaller companies with more limited financial means have no chance to participate in the process.

Read more: https://github.com/shuding/react-wrap-balancer#browser-support-information"))};self.__wrap_n!=1&&self.__wrap_b(":R4tm:",1)A new law has been enacted, granting postal employees the right to sound the alarm about drugs in letters and parcels. However, this information has not reached everyone, as shown by an examination by P1 program Kaliber and P4 channels in Western Sweden. A drug dealer, pseudonym Johan, has been sending drugs via Postnord for nine years without being detected. 'Postnord is very reliable. They think they're doing a good job,' he says. The police estimate that a million shipments with drugs are sent with domestic mail every year, hence the hope in the revised postal law introduced at the turn of the year. The law gives postal employees and deputies the right to alert the police if they discover suspicious letters and parcels in the flow. Earlier, strict confidentiality prevailed. A major responsibility was also placed on postal operators, where Postnord is the largest, to educate the deputies about the new law. Emiliano, who runs a kiosk and postal agency in Bengtsfors, is unaware of the new law. 'It's a bit strange when there's a change in the law. We also work with tobacco. Then we get information in good time,' he states. As a random sample, Sveriges Radio visited a hundred postal agencies in Western Sweden to ask what they know about the new postal law. Fifty had not heard of the law at all. A large part of the other fifty had learned about it through the police or media, and not by postal operators. Alexis Larsson, security chief at Postnord, needs to follow up on this with their retail organization. 'It seems not many are aware of this. That's what I take from the conversation,' he says. 'Johan' is not his real name. The reporters in the feature were Skob Salihi, Ida Nord√©n and Sanna Ekstedt Larsson.

Read more: https://github.com/shuding/react-wrap-balancer#browser-support-information"))};self.__wrap_n!=1&&self.__wrap_b(":R4tm:",1)The costs for items like sick leave and parental leave are predicted to increase by nearly 30 billion kronor in the coming years, according to Ren√© Blomberg, the forecast chief at the Social Insurance Agency (F√∂rs√§kringskassan). This significant increase is naturally impactful on the state budget, forcing the government to find these 30 billion kronor from somewhere. According to the new forecasts provided by the Social Insurance Agency to the government, the expenses for social insurance this year are expected to reach 235 billion kronor. This figure is slightly lower than last year and accounts for about one-fifth of the total state budget. However, next year, the costs for social insurance are expected to gradually rise. Within three years, they are expected to increase by almost 30 billion kronor in comparison to this year. The costs for the care of children and compensation for parental leave and sick leave are increasing in line with wage increases and inflation. The levels of compensation are expected to be higher in the future. The Social Insurance Agency also estimates that more people will be on sick leave for longer periods, resulting in increased costs. Recent changes in sickness insurance regulations mean that more people are staying on sick leave instead of returning to work.

This year, security has been ramped up, with measures such as metal detectors in some exam venues. However, these measures do not extend to all locations, sparking a debate around fairness and the potential for cheating. Some participants who sat for the exams today reported that their venues did not have metal detectors. They suggested that, theoretically, cheating could be possible. However, the potential penalties, such as a two-year ban, make it a risky venture. Before entering the exam room, candidates must remove their bags and outerwear and leave their mobile phones outside. In some venues, there are also metal detectors and security personnel who have the right to physically search candidates for hidden electronics. The University and Higher Education Council, which organizes these exams, has been tight-lipped about the locations of the metal detectors and the cost of the increased security measures. They argue that revealing such information could aid potential cheaters. √Öke L√§rnefalk, Press Officer at the University and Higher Education Council, stated that implementing metal detectors in all venues would require thousands of security personnel and could potentially lead to an exam fee increase. Cheating scandals have marred the exam in the past. Five years ago, several cheating rings were discovered. In 2020, three main culprits were sentenced to prison, and about twenty participants received conditional sentences and fines. Those caught cheating this year will face a two-year ban.

This information has been confirmed by the Sea and Air Rescue Center. The ship, which had a total of 71 people on board, was en route from Trelleborg to Karlshamn at the time of the incident.All passengers and part of the crew have been evacuated from the vessel. The shipping company, TT Line, has refrained from giving any interviews. However, they have posted on their website that they are working with insurance companies and Swedish authorities to assess the extent of the damage to the ship.It has been established that there is a hole in the hull and that the ferry is taking on water. A sea rescue operation is still ongoing at the location. According to Karl-Johan Thyleg√•rd, the Sea Rescue Leader at the Sea and Air Rescue Center, the situation is being taken very seriously due to the ship's grounded position and the hole in its hull.Since the ferry ran aground, oil and diesel have leaked into the sea. The Coast Guard has initiated a preliminary investigation regarding violations of maritime law. They also disclosed that the spill is being investigated separately and that a preliminary investigation for environmental crimes may be added.

Read more: https://github.com/shuding/react-wrap-balancer#browser-support-information"))};self.__wrap_n!=1&&self.__wrap_b(":R4tm:",1)The Swedish Board of Agriculture has given the green light to the cross-country ski race, √Ñngelbrechtsloppet, scheduled to take place in Norrberg this February, despite the race passing through a restricted area where wild boars affected by African swine fever have been found. We hear from state epidemiologist, Carl St√•hl, from the National Veterinary Institute.The race is set to occur outside what is referred to as the 'core area.' As a result, the judgment has been made that the race can proceed under the conditions set. This is in line with the current situation that the infection is largely confined to the area around Fagersta, a small region with a diameter of approximately 5-6 kilometers.For the first time, a large outward-facing activity is being permitted in the area in V√§stmanland where dead wild boars affected by the African swine fever were found in early September. About 2,000 people usually participate in the √Ñngelbrechtsloppet. The Board of Agriculture has decided to grant an exception to the restrictions of being in the forest and fields. However, there are requirements that limitations must be in place regarding where the audience can stand during the competition, and that equipment should be cleaned after the race.The National Veterinary Institute was consulted and endorsed that the race could be held in a way that is safe from an infection prevention perspective. However, this may be reassessed, says Carl St√•hl. If the infection moves, spreading and being found in this area where the race will be held, a different recommendation will be given to the Board of Agriculture. This could put the exception at risk.
